You can have a great time on an Argosy Cruise. Boats leave from the waterfront at Pier 55 and cruise through Puget Sound or from AGC Marina and cruise through Lake Union and Lake Washington. The boats have bars, good food and friendly staff. You'll see and learn things you'll never even notice without getting on a boat with an experienced captain as your guide.
Great experience with Lake Washington cruise

Great tour of bay!Comfortable, headsets in many languages with an informative and interesting description of sights.Great overall value with snack bar on board.We did the hour tour which was exactly enough time too see it all.Loved it and it was the perfect way to start our couples getaway!

We had our company Christmas party Monday, December 7th aboard the Celebrations boat. It was wonderful! Everyone was extremely accommodating. Matt, our rep, came up with ideas to fit within our budget - and had immense patience with our endless questions. Nick, the captain, asked where we wanted to go (I assumed there was a strict route, nice surprise) and set up Christmas music to play throughout the evening. Rachel, our on board contact, did EVERYTHING, so I was able to enjoy myself instead of working the entire evening. I felt so guilty, I tried to help, but she insisted with such kindness. Corsica, our bartender, was so sweet - and quick! There was never a line for drinks. The boat was decorated beautifully - and somehow they arranged for the rain to stop ;) I'd love to have our party with them every year.

It's easy to bypass this incredible museum when you are visiting Seattle and going to the famous Space Needle. But plan to spend an hour or more at this museum. I could have wandered through it all day. The glass exhibits are so colorful and gorgeous. Pieces are unique and whimsical. I had not read much about it, and was so surprised at how spectacular it was.  The museum has many large indoor  rooms, and the garden is unbelievable. You really have to see it.There is also a Cafe (check out the decor even if you don't eat there.) and a lovely gift shop.  Highly recommended!

Highly recommend!  If you get the City Pass, I would say the best things are the Space Needle and this museum.  The museum was beautiful, and well lit.  There is also a glass blowing demonstration.  Definitely worth the admission.  There are also street performers right outside and a hot dog stand where you can get authentic Seattle hot dog.  Take some time in the garden and atrium to get shots of the Space Needle and glass art together. On a side note the bathrooms have collections of bottle openers and there is an empty side cafe near the bathrooms with collections of accordions , dolls and other collectibles.  Itâ€™s worth a look.

Such a wonderful museum. Wonderful exhibit. The craftsmanship and display of all the glass is incredible. The colors, patterns, and sheer size is something that needs to be seen. There are also live glass blowing demonstrations that allow you to see the amount of effort and creativity that goes into making just one small piece. A must see for locals and tourists alike.

I did not make firm plans to go to this museum while I was in Seattle because I was not sure if I'd have time to, however, I'm glad that I was able to find the time to go. I arrived around 4:00 pm, which was great as tickets are discounted after 4 pm. The museum took about an hour to go through, and that included a glass blowing show. The glass was beautiful - I never thought you could do what Chihuly did to glass. He created some stunning art with it. The glass blowing show was interesting also. They have a gift shop that sells some of the glass artwork (for a very hefty price, of course).

Wonderful & beautiful exhibit. We had the fire roasted pizza for lunch with a carafe of wine. It was a good deal and very tasty. The glass blowing demonstration was very interesting and the garden was nice. Only down side was it seemed to be a small exhibit for the price, but still fun & very beautiful. I would highly recommend it if you haven't seen Chihuly's work.

reviews.text:
Wow okay...wow. This place earns every star.  The store is adorable and tiny, and an efficient use of space and time (much like English establishments maybe?). You come in, order your food, eat it at one of the few spots that will likely open up because the size of the place forces everyone to stick to their business, eat their food and leave fast so that others can eat theirs. It makes people considerate--what a brilliant use of square footage.

The counter is lined with small jars of jam and marmalade you can buy, you can watch your food being made, and the back wall is lined with an Alice in Wonderland mural. It. Is. Perfect.

And the food: it's all crumpets--savory and sweet, and delicious! I was able to try the 'Vermont' (maple butter, walnuts and creme cheese); the smoked salmon, creme cheese and cucumber; and the ricotta with rasberry preserves. Heaven. I kept saying heaven while eating too.

They also have a great selection of teas and espresso as well as fresh orange juice. 

This is probably one of favorite food places on the entire continent. I have their store bag (everything of theirs is exponentially cute) framed and up in my room. ðŸ’•

We've been coming here for the past 6 years. We visit Seattle every 2 years and our first stop is consistently The Crumpet Shop at Pike place market. I cannot get enough of this place! Over 6 years, their smoked salmon Crumpet has remained exactly the same. That's bloody amazing! It's literally the best Crumpet shop I've been to either side of the pond. If you're ever in town you absolutely have to visit this place. The staff are always friendly and helpful!

Crunchy, dripping with butter, layered with eggs or maple butter, health food this is not. But it is delicious.

The Crumpet Shop offers crumpets, which are like thicker, richer English muffins, and several choices of toppings. There's also a great selection of teas and coffees. 

They aren't cheap, but nothing in the market or rest of the downtown area is. The staff are very pleasant and helpful.
Great for breakfast. Lot of savory and sweet crumpet option. I had the Pesto-Tomato-Cheese and Maple-walnut-Cream. Both were excellent, but I enjoyed the sweet one more.

I had a crumpet with egg and English cheese plus a cup of Earl Grey tea. The tea was great and the crumpet/egg/cheese was DELICIOUS. Going back tomorrow with a friend! Charming atmosphere that feels intimate and welcoming. :) Highly recommended.

reviews.text: This is an interesting place to spend an hour or three in Seattle and the price was right â€” free! It was interesting to watch the film about the gold rush and the two floors of exhibits were well done. I loved the way it allowed me to choose and learn about a particular person as I went through. The gift shop was small and nice.

I was just sitting across the street in a nice cafe where I realized this museum. It is free. It is small and cute. Worth checking out and wonder along the photo stories and also the materials used during the Gold Rush. Sort of a hidden gem, hard to find its entrance
Great way to learn the history about the city rain or shine!  Guides are very friendly and enthusiastic about the information they're sharing. The best part of the experience is it's free!

Very cool Klondike Gold Rush museum, with several interesting facts and documents on display. There was a movie showing during my visit, which was very interesting as well. A bit small, perhaps, but it sheds some light on Seattle's rise to prominence!

The museum was better than I expected.  The admission is free, the employees are very friendly and helpful. We spent nearly an hour here. We liked how they identified specific people to follow their story, and the roughly half hour movie is worth watching.  There is even a section of history about the building the museum is in. Parking was right across street, however it is costly like everywhere else in Seattle. Main negative is the huge number of people sleeping on the sidewalks here. I've read about Seattle's homeless problem and is it sure on display in this area, from the tent city in the park nearby to those in sleeping bags all around the parking area.

reviews.text:
An abundant wonderland filled with every possible pastry and confection that could exceed your heart's desire, but coffee lovers be aware: they do not serve espresso.

The quality is matched by the price, which is a little spendy compared to competing locations that cater to one's sweet tooth, but the range is still affordable considering the wide selection of small batch creations.

There is no indoor seating and you may need to visit more than once to get a good look at the options because of how busy the line gets. But all the more reason to come back and try one of everything!

The grilled cheese was DIVINE. And donâ€™t miss the key lime pie. This was a great stop for lunch in downtown Seattle. They only have a few seats to sit outside, so plan on waiting a bit for a seat, or take your meal to go. Really friendly staff, restroom is inside the larger restaurant.

Granola.

All you need to do is try their granola. Fresh, wholesome and hearty. This is an awesome treat whether you're stopping by to sit outside or a quick treat for your partner when heading home from work!
I love this place. Breakfast sandwiches are the bomb! Get a peanut butter sandwich to go.

I thought it was pretty good...not 5-star French good, but good. I appreciated that their sweets were not overly sweet. Staff was friendly and helpful when asking for a recommendation. Place is small and outdoor seating is limited.

The only thing we didn't like was the truffle experience! I got so excited thinking we were getting chocolate, but instead it was truffle oil and salt, which I didn't like at all!

Had a great time during the tour, we had Jerry and although quirky he was very informative and personable. Overall I would def recommend it to anyone wanting to enjoy pikes place and learn about the history. Also la buona tavola was amazing. Who knew that I was a truffle guy?!

During my visit to the Pacific Northwest I took the Taste of Pike Place Market with Seattle Food Tours and I was not disappointed. I had a limited of time in Seattle and this tour was a great introduction to one of Seattle's most iconic attractions. My expectations were surpassed with the amount of stops and places we visited on the tour. The variety of the food was a great way to experience the diversity of the market. Tastings of authentic northwest clam chowder, gelato, salmon, crumpets, pickle brine, meat and crackers, and fresh fruit were among the foods I thoroughly enjoyed. The serving sizes were more than enough and by the end of the tour I was very full and happy. 

Our tour guide Penny was very funny and it was clear she was very passionate about Seattle and the Market. Her exuberant personality made exploring the market an eye opening experience. She also served as a facilitator, so it made getting to know other people on the tour easy and natural. I took home great souvenirs from my time at the Pike Place and even better memories of the people and the food.

I experiences several new places that I hadn't been before and our tour guide was great. I would recommend this tour to out of towners as well as locals. The food was great and it was a fun experience. Thank you Seattle Food Tours!
Tour was OK for the price.  We really enjoyed Jerry, his knowledge and personality was the best part of the tour.  Pretty expensive for what you get.

reviews.text: This place is a coffee lovers paradise.  Line to get in moved very fast.   Food and coffee was perfect.  Only con i can state is seating is very limited.  You have to grab a table "before" you order.  Not always ideal because someone then has to hold the table while someone orders.  Great experience worker really treat customers well here.

It's kind of feels like a craft brewery, but for coffee. If you're a Starbucks fan, or coffee lover in general, it's worth checking out (even if you don't usually love Starbucks like myself). The inside of it is spacious, looks very cool, and has large coffee roasting machinery running off to the side. You can purchase hard-to-find unique blends of coffee and plenty of merchandise. Has a coffee bar for trying their exclusive drinks, a real bar, and Italian food. The special coffee drinks they have are actually really interesting and unique. If you can find a free table it's a pretty cool place to enjoy a coffee.

Awesome place to try unique selections and blends of food and drinks menu. Large place with enough space and variety of merchandise. The menu itself is unique, from coffee blends, to signature coffee based cocktails and fast food. Would suggest Origin Flight, Espresso Martini Flight and The Whisky Cloud from the menu for drinks, pretty flavourful. The venue gives a very industrial setting look with coffee making process and machines seen in full glory. Busy spot with few mins wait time in line, but fast moving. Very different experience than a typical round the corner Starbucks shop.

This Reserve was beautifully designed. I suggest going in the evening. It was much less busy and kinda relaxing. The menu at a reserve is much different and honestly more classy than the average Starbucks. The different menu does mean slightly higher prices. This location has exclusive merchandise and products that can be a great addition to your own home coffee set up or can be a great gift.

I would have loved to try a cocktail here and would have been willing to pay their sky high prices for one, but they aren't clear on what tables you can order from but require you to have a table to order. All tables are first come first served. It's really confusing, crowded, and feels like a black Friday race to try and get seating. I don't understand why they don't just put in a host stand for the tables/seating so you don't have to prowl around people enjoying their food and beverage like a predator. The coffee making was cool and we appreciated the demonstration.

I had a really yummy apricot croissant and tea on a busy weekday morning with family. The line was long but moved fast enough. Seating was like playing a game of musical chairs. The baguette I bought to bring home was crisp, fresh and delicious.

Expect a line to grab exquisite french pastries but don't let it deter to not try it. You'll regret not checking it out yourself. The fresh baked croissants, tarts and such are absolutely wonderful. Sweet and tasty with a good amount of buttery goodness baked into these amazing morsels for foodies like myself. Definitely can't skip on this place!
Food is good!  I've been here a few times, and the staff is really nice too!  Lines are usually pretty long if you come during popular times.  Theres pretty good seating though.

Spent around 50 bucks to try almost everything. The croissants are all fire. Light, airy, fluffy, crispy. Got a big loaf of bread, which was also quality. Good fermentation, crispy, clean, and healthy tasting. The macaroons were also excellent. Not a fan of their savory breads, cold and out of place. Most bakeries are one dimensional, chemical like, and bland tasting. La Panier is all about sophisticated flavors and quality. The coffee was good and balanced, but took about 15 minutes. Went on a Saturday, so it's understandable. I'll try to make it on a weekday.

This is absolutely the best french bakery I have been to. Everything they serve is absolute perfection. I have eaten here probably 10 times and tried a variety of food & drinks and have never not been totally impressed. The staff are really friendly given how busy they always are. They are also very efficient and can move people quick enough that you shouldn't let a line out of the door intimidate you.

Made to order teriyaki menu is excellent, fresh vegetables, quality meat, delicious clean flavor and well prepared, not saucy, perfect amount of spicy kick, one of the best teriyaki in downtown Seattle. Made to order sandwich deli and usual small grocery items and beverages. Old and a bit dingy feeling but courteous service and excellent hot food! Don't judge quality from exterior. Convenient downtown location to hotels, office buildings, library and I-5.
I couldn't find a single community in the grocery, not even in the frozen section! Just kidding. Actually, it is a wonderful store.

If you got a sunny windy weather and a sail in the middle of the workday - you're going to enjoy it a lot! It's like a meditation retreat. And commonly they have a discount for the midday sails on the working days - so don't forget to check their web site for deals.

Beautiful way to spend an afternoon. I really like how they don't serve food, because it simplifies everything and avoids feeling bad for bringing your own. Just stop at a sandwish/wine shop and bring your own. They provide a big cooler on board to store drinks. Also no spoken tour etc. Just simple sailing with the ocean and the breeze.

We did the sunset sailing experience and it was wonderful. The scenery was beautiful, the boat was excellent, and the crew was clearly very skilled and experienced. Make sure to dress warm for the sunset sail because the temperature will drop drastically. There's a bathroom on board, so the 2.5 hour trip isn't so bad.
Nice crew. Kid friendly. Lots of fun!

I bought a couple of Gold star tickets as a gift for my boyfriends birthday.We spent the whole day in Seattle, WA .I recommend going during the sunset hours. Hats the time I went on the cruise with my bf.We had so much fun.There is free food, entertainment, and one free beverage included with the purchase of each ticket.I personally recommend this as a date for couples .

reviews.text:
It's a wall. Covered in multi colored chewing gum. It's gross and beautiful at the same time. I've personally seen someone putting their lips to the wall trying to stick their gum, and surprisingly, no one was grossed out! It's upto you if want to stick your gum to the wall but I do advice taking a picture here, cos that wall makes for an amazing background!

Also, remember that the wall looks different in the night (maybe even more beautiful, if you ask me). You might like it.

Have you been through this gum alley and stopped to see the creative artwork? It's a fascinating experience as one goes down a small narrow ancient stair, below the south end of the market. 

On a beautiful sunny day it's filled with tourists speaking many different languages in a relatively confined alley, one hardly can miss it.  The canvas stretches from brick, plaster, window sills, louvers, poor gas meter and even street signs. It's an experience as long as one's business does not front this decorated alley.

So glad this Seattle attraction continues to give kids of all ages a cool place to visit. It's so conveniently located and a perfect place for little ones to enjoy when they've had enough of shopping and sightseeing. Make sure to make a personal contribution.
A cool little tourist destination below pikes. To make it special, you may want to add your own piece. It is a little gross but, it's a Seattle tradition/destination.

Pretty gross but totally awesome. It was a bit hard to find for me but it's located in an alley. If facing the Pike Public Market sign, go downstairs and make a left into Post Alley and you'll see the DNA extravaganza. There was construction going on when I was there in mid-October 2014 but one can still see the gum wall. Some people get artistic and make symbols or artwork with the gum. I saw the Space Needle, in gum form which was pretty cool. Other than looking at it for 5 seconds there isn't anything else special. Gum Wall you've received your 5-seconds of fame.

reviews.text: Slightly pricey, but well worth the cost. A good selection of crust, sauce, meats, veggies and many types of cheese allow you to make any type of pizza you could want. The personal pizza is a good size as well. The wood fired ovens it is all baked in just adds to the taste.

I was visiting from out of town, and didn't realize this was the original MOD Pizza! The staff was friendly and they work hard and quickly, even on a busy day. The pizza is delicious!
The only weird thing was, there were messages saying they make the dough "fresh every day", but the dough was clearly coming out of a pre-packaged box... It feels deceptive...
At least it tasted good.

Great food and fast service. At my last visit they were supper busy, but I still got my food in a timely manner AND had a place to sit!

Both pizza and salad offerings are delicious and fresh. Not a wide drink selection, but they have the essentials.

Easily one of the best pizza chains, if not the best. The service is extremely fast and friendly (especially Stanley, he's amazing), the pizza is fantastic, the prices are cheap, and whoever picks this music at this location has excellent taste. I can't reccomend their "Tyler" pizza enough, it's easily one of the best I've had.
Great pizza for the price. Love the pricing structure: 1 price for a size of pizza. And they served some great craft beer too!

I came here because of the hype and it did not disappoint. The clam chowder was meat and we'll seasoned. However, the sourdough bread bowl is what impressed me the most. It was soft and flavorful.

Also, the price was not bad at all for a well known and popular restaurant. I spent under $20 and left completely full.

Never knew chowder was my favourite dish until I came to this phenomenal establishment. You can see why theyâ€™ve won so many awards year in and year out. Absolutely delicious and a must visit for any traveller to Seattle and every local with the opportunity.  New England Chowder in a bread bowl cannot be recommended enough! More than worth the wait.

I love this place.  However, don't be frightened away from the crowds.  The line moves quickly and the tables have signs on them stating not to save seats so you will find a place to sit when you get your food.  I recommend anything with lobster in it. Oh, and there is plenty of free extra bread and butter.

The New England clam chowder is hands down the best chowder on the menu and the best I've ever had. The lobster rolls are also fantastic. Can't go wrong with a Connecticut style butter roll. The line looks long but moves super fast. If you want a shorter line then come earlier in the morning and around Mondays and Tuesdays. Ordering pickup online is also a good way to skip the line.

Super delicious chowders and sandwiches! The sourdough "bowls" were fresh and took the experience to a whole new level!
The staff are friendly and helpful, and despite the big line up take the time to answer any questions. 
Reletively big seating area (outdoor) to enjoy your food.

reviews.text: Cannot tell you how much I enjoyed this tour. It was EXACTLY what I was looking for. The tour guide was super engaging and fun, and he touched on everything from indigenous history, to the founding and development of Seattle, to the current culture and scene -- even recommending places for Happy Hour! He was truly a wealth of information. Anything he didn't talk during the main portions of the tour that I was curious about I could pull him aside while walking to the next spot and he was able to fill in the gaps for me every time. Have so much appreciation for this experience.

The best walking tour I have EVER had!  This was the most memorable tour because our guide (and owner) Jake, knew everything about the city! He was extremely passionate about what he does and it made the difference.  If you are looking for an amazing in-depth look at the Emerald City, look no more!  This tour will fascinate you!  Book it now!

Loved this tour. It was fun and engaging and Jake, the tour guide, was funny and knew so much! I went on the Market experience tour which takes you through Pikes Place Market and I cannot believe how much I would have missed if I hadn't gone on this tour. This is a must if you are new to Seattle!!!

This was an excellent tour.  Jake was our tour guide and did an awesome job explaining the history of various parts of Seattle and was very funny.  He was very knowledgeable about the restaurants and things to do for fun in the area.

The only unfortunate part of the tour today was that I got hit with an egg someone threw, which exploded all over my back and got on another woman as well.

We had an excellent experience on the Seattle 101 tour ran by Jake. We were given a great amount of information about Seattle, which gave us the confidence to explore the city deeper on our own. reviews.text: We took the ride along flight for a couple hours with two stops. We flew in the beaver and had an amazing experience. Easy boarding and great take offs and landings on our flights. This is a must do for people who have an afternoon free in the Seattle area and want to do something off the beaten path with lasting memories.

Recently did a round trip weekend to Victoria with my girlfriend. We took a piston Beaver there and a turbo Otter back. This is what air travel should be like. It was easy to check in, the boarding process was quick, and it seemed like an adventure. The airplanes seem to be well kept also. The only downside (if you are not a fan of flying) is it can get a bit bumpy at times since you're much lower in altitude and in smaller planes. I would definitely do this again.

I love flying Kenmore Air. Recently, we flew from Lake Washington to Victoria, BC. Although we have flown with them many times before, itâ€™s just plan fun and worth the price of admission to take off from water, fly at low altitude and land in the middle of the hustle and bustle of Victoria Harbour. As we deplaned we were literally just steps away from our hostâ€™s boat. 
On the return trip our friends had moved and were now moored At Roche  Harbor Resort on San Juan Island, Wa. When it was time to leave we stepped from the boat and walked to the end of the dock. Within a few minutes Kenmore Air landed and taxied into their tie-up area. A few minutes later weâ€™re accelerating across the water of the Harbor as we takeoff en route to Lake Union; next door to downtown Seattle. When we land a shuttle is waiting to whisk us away to Sea-Tac Airport for our flight home to California. An incredible trip where Kenmore made the travel so convenient and uncomplicated! They are wonderful to work with. You might consider a romantic 2 night getaway surprise for your honey. Itâ€™s easy as pie! Trust me, you will be rewarded!
Kenmore Air is incredible! The staff is always friendly and knowledgeable and it's the best way to get up to the San Juans! The ride is always smooth and easy and so beautiful.
They are really nice to you and everything was clean und tidy. We were there much too early so there is not much to spend time on... Next time i will arrive a little later.

reviews.text: This was truly a great find in the busy Pike Place Market that lives up to the hype! Prior to our visit to Seattle, my husband did research on restaurants and the Market Grill was listed. We went there this past Sunday and we were not disappointed. Itâ€™s a small stand in the bustling Pike Place market but donâ€™t let the small size fool you. The staff was nice and super friendly and the food was exceptional. My husband ordered the salmon platter and I got the Icelandic cod sandwich. The fish was so fresh and perfectly seasoned. My husband also sampled the clam chowder which he said was truly delicious. I wish we had gotten the name of the guy that took our order. He was super friendly and welcomed us as if we were personal guests at his home. The chef, Jason, was also friendly and did a superb job preparing our meal. Seating is somewhat of an issue (limited number of barstools) but the turnover rate was pretty quick. I would highly recommend this restaurant.

This is a small shack in the busy pike market. Although space is limited and the stools are accounted for, the turnover rate is very efficient. We ordered a large clam chowder and the catch of the day (Icelandic Cod sandwich) and it really hit the spot. They grill your desired meat feet away from you which anyone can appreciate. Staff was down to earth and nice enough. Definitely recommend ðŸ‘Œ

Truly, Seattle food does not get better than this. You can keep your fancy restaurants in downtown, this sit down at a bar and order food is the best in the city. Grilled salmon sandwich with a bowl of the best chowder anywhere and a coke is literally heaven. Heaven I tell you!!! If youâ€™re in town for any length of time, do...not...pass...up the opportunity to eat here. You will absolutely not be disappointed.

This was really fun.  It has a bit of something for everyone.   I would have preferred some areas to be bigger but it was still good.  My kids loved the sound room!  They enjoyed learning about how the instruments worked.

Absolutely fabulous place to go!! With many galleries to explore and look at including a hands on music lab. Had an amazing time and well worth the time!! Friendly and helpful staff. Parking available across the street and adjacent to the Seattle Center!! Makes for a wonderful day!

The only slight disappointment was the length of time in the Underground. This is not the tour for you if you want to see a large portion of Seattle's underground. It really is the stories that make the tour. We would definitely recommend for anyone who likes ghost stories and wants a little excitement and terror in their evening.

Fun little tour of the area around Pioneer Square. I thought there would be more underground, but a good tour if you want to learn the history of some of the Paranormal Activity in regards to building the city on top of the underground city.

We were so happy to find this little place just down the street from the one we were headed for. The people were so lovely and so fun and the whole experience was fantastic!! Our tour guide was phenomenal! I would and will recommend this tour company to anyone who wants a historical tour of Seattle. Thank you so much!

Richard was amazing, I learnt so much about Seattle and I liked the fact he patiently explained with so much information. The tour itself is pretty awesome , wild history and great humor by Richard along the way. Unfortunately I didn't have cash in hand to tip him

reviews.text: Amazing tour! My wife and I were visiting from Philly and took the Pike Place tour with Savor Seattle (Caitlin was our tour guide). Caitlin did a phenomenal job leading us up and down Pike Place Market with tons of great Seattle and food tips/history along the way. We got to skip the very long lines at some of Pike Place's most popular attractions to get delicious food including Russian pastries and clam chowder (with equally-delicious vegetarian options for my wife). At the end, we even got a VIP pass with coupons to several additional Pike Place vendors. Definitely worth doing while you're in Seattle, and in our case we'll likely do it again next time we're in town!

One of the best food tours we have done!  We did the Early Access VIP Tour of Pike Place Market.  It was a well thought out and tasty tour, but finding good food in the Pike Place Market is like shooting fish in a barrel.  The tour provides a good overview of the highlights of the market and includes a lot of stops at several great places. Mark a Seattle native was an incredible tour guide and really loves his job, food, and Seattle.  He was a real treat and you should ask for him on your tour.  He was very attentive and was eager for questions and to provide excellent suggestions for anything specific we were looking to find.  We have been on food tours all around the world and this one was one of the best we have done.

This was my first food tour and an experience I will treasure always. Our guide, Katya, was absolutely remarkable. She remembered every single person's name with ease and made sure each person felt included and important. Art museum includes different cultural elements and attractive traditional things.  Art museum is an important place to cover while visiting Seattle.

reviews.text: Sky View Observatory has an amazing view of Seattle, a complete 360 degree view and from 73 floors above to be exact. Nothing is obstructed since it is located in the tallest building in downtown, Seattle. We have been here several times and everyone we've spoken to is very friendly and knowledgeable. And if they aren't, they find the right people who can help you. They throw some really great events that I would highly recommend checking out such as Pride events, 4th of July, yoga, Sunset experiences, etc. The events get pretty busy and packed but if you go on any regular day, the views are breathtaking and it's rather tranquil. They also have fun games like Connect Four if you just want to sit and take in the views. Regardless, definitely a place to check out with the whole family or a perfect place for date night!

Twice as tall and half the cost of the Space Needle. Plus: a 360-view of the city and bay from the center of the action; great food at "down to earth" prices; view-rooms to hang out and play supplied games for as long as you want; explanations of the landmarks you're looking at painted on the interior walls; optional photos of your group with Bigfoot; and a fast, dedicated large bank of elevators that eliminates lines. Also, the Needle is nicer to look at than sit atop. 

One caveat: parking. As with most of the rest of downtown Seattle, a visitor can spend hours looking for street parking, park blocks away for an exorbitant price, or try to park in the heart of the action for an insanely expensive price and probably be turned down because the lot is full. Cities like this have merely to look to Provo, Utah to see how plentiful free parking turns a dying city center into a vibrant communal destination.

Great experience. The Sky View provides wonderful views of the city in a 360 degree walk around. Youâ€™re totally enclosed the entire time, but the views are spectacular. The lines and crowds were nonexistent on Sunday afternoon - making the beautiful scenery easy to take in.

Went at 4 pm on a sunny day, Aug 13. 2019.  We were the only people in the lift and there were two or three couples up top when we got there. The views are amazing, the staff are really nice, the drinks were $10 each.  It was a really great experience, much better than the crowded space needle. I would highly recommend this as a must do in Seattle.

It's the view on the 73th floor that counts. A full panoramic view of Seattle and all its surroundings on a beautiful clear sky is fabulous. You can purchase tickets online or on-the-spot. The experience starts in the elevator and once you reach the Observatory, the scenic view hits you. We saw ferries transporting cars, the highway traffic, the Space Needle and the Stadiums, the harbor and many more. It is very educational for the kids too. Food and beverage can be purchased while you enjoy the view. Parking is available on the street. A must-see place in Seattle in my humble opinion!

This was really fun.  It has a bit of something for everyone.   I would have preferred some areas to be bigger but it was still good.  My kids loved the sound room!  They enjoyed learning about how the instruments worked.

Absolutely fabulous place to go!! With many galleries to explore and look at including a hands on music lab. Had an amazing time and well worth the time!! Friendly and helpful staff. Parking available across the street and adjacent to the Seattle Center!! Makes for a wonderful day!

This is one of the greatest museums I have ever been to. I personally loved the Nirvana and Fantasy sections but the Jam Room was a great way to really give everyone an experience of music. This building is like no other it's one of a kind . It's a big part of Seattle.  This is a fun place to visit.  I love it here . I have seen some very cool shows here. I took a video here of Paul Allen playing guitar.  It was a cool night  Thank You Mo Pop & Paul Allen

I absolutely love this museum! The exhibits were all really cool and showcased a lot of unique artifacts such as film props and costumes. I particularly enjoyed the exhibit on horror, as it's a genre that has contributed greatly to our culture but is often viewed as less worthy of study than other media genres. The special exhibit on Marvel was really cool too! It was interesting to see how the stories have been translated/changed for different media formats as well as over time.

This was really fun.  It has a bit of something for everyone.   I would have preferred some areas to be bigger but it was still good.  My kids loved the sound room!  They enjoyed learning about how the instruments worked.

Absolutely fabulous place to go!! With many galleries to explore and look at including a hands on music lab. Had an amazing time and well worth the time!! Friendly and helpful staff. Parking available across the street and adjacent to the Seattle Center!! Makes for a wonderful day!

This is one of the greatest museums I have ever been to. I personally loved the Nirvana and Fantasy sections but the Jam Room was a great way to really give everyone an experience of music. The architecture is beautiful, even if a bit easy to get lost in (but your in Seattle anyways...), and a great use of copper as a main color. If your in Seattle and need absorb yourself in the history of all things popular, come here.

reviews.text: This was a great place for a quick bite. Clean facilities and upbeat workers. Management is treating them right. Just like any place, it can get busy but if you time your visit you can be in and out quick. Consider checking out the menu on the website first to make a quick trip here a little faster.

Place is really talked a lot about. Food was decent, not bad by any means. But I was a little disappointed honestly. Granted I do judge Mac and cheese harshly, and it wasn't bad Mac and cheese but something about it was off. It took a few bites for it to get good. When it does though the flavors come out but I feel there is something just a little off about it. But definitely not bad. The grilled cheese was decent but I really wish they'd use another bread other Than Sour dough, and like the Mac and cheese it took a few bites for it to get good. Cheese curdled Were pretty good though. I'd say people can come judge for themselves what the hype is about but if there's a huge line....... It's OK to skip it.

Love the food.  Be prepared to wait in line!  It's also really pricey, but I don't care, I took home a really yummy wheel of brie and some cheese curds; they have samples; and finally I ate a really good grilled cheese sandwich and took a bite of amazing mac n cheese.  However, there's barely any seating, but what are you gonna do about that?  It's a small place in a busy area, you can't expect a lot of open seats.

The food here is EXCELLENT. We are always super excited when we are able to find Beecher's Flagship cheese at our local supermarket (we're from out of state). You can definitely taste the quality when you eat here.

Best mac and cheese I've had in my entire life. No joke. And it's super cool how you can see them hand making the cheese even when walking by the store. If you're not hungry at the moment you should at least stop in to pick up something to take home. Also a great place for gifts.

reviews.text: I have never been one to take the "tourist scenic route" when visiting a new city, but this is one tour that I am so glad I took!!  My husband and I had an amazing time learning about the history of Seattle and Jim narrates it beautifully!  He made learning history so much fun and left us wanting to learn more about "Underground Seattle"  Can't wait to go back and learn more.  I highly recommend this tour for anyone traveling to that gorgeous city!!

My partner and I had just one day to explore Seattle, and our driver recommended us to do an underground tour. We ended up at Beneath The Streets. The tour was led by Jim Gall, a charismatic, knowledgeable guide who made the history of Seattle come to life, was very entertaining, and made a point of learning everyone's names and where we were all from which gave the tour a more personal feel which was really nice. In short, beneath the streets is a very enjoyable and informative tour and I would highly recommend it. Just one note - be sure to keep in mind that very little of the city's underground has been preserved so don't expect a labyrinth or you may be disappointed! :)

This was as just as educational as it was entertaining. Great guides with tons of knowledge. Jim even found us after our tour was complete to report that someone from our group left a cell phone. Her asked us to let them know if we saw them and then stood at a central location to try to find them. What great customer service!
Dave, the tour guide, is very knowledgeable of the history and had a good sense of humor.  I really enjoyed the in-depth explanation of how it came to be with all the underground sidewalks.

If you're weighing the choice between Beneath The Streets and Bill Speidel's Underground Tour, I'd encourage you to try Beneath The Streets! The tour is more intimate (groups will max out at half the size) and factual, and our guide Jim gave us some fantastic recommendations for what to do afterwards, giving us an excuse to visit Smith Tower!

I won't spoil the sights you'll see, but your guide will give you a glimpse at early Seattle and the modern establishments that still connect to it! Absolutely worth the cost of admission, and if you are early, there's a spooky museum connected to the business that you can check out for free.

reviews.text: Upon walking up to the library, you are just taken aback by the beautiful architecture of this building, already. The library's structure is so inviting and calls you in, really. Loved the layout of it. Such a great, free resource for the city. The staff was very friendly and helpful and the library was extremely clean and well kept. They had a red hallway that wasn't there when my friend was last here, which made for some fun photo ops. The tall glass windows were beautiful and added a little something extra to the ambience of the place. Beautiful, peaceful everything a library should be.

Centrally located Public Library right in the heart of downtown Seattle, very near all transit and several parking garages. This stunning display of architecture is a beautiful centerpiece of the otherwise skyscraping business district.

There are many grand, expansive reading rooms, as well as a great number of cozy nooks throughout the building. The library is kept as a very nice, quiet environment for reading and studying. There is a no cell phone rule, that I believe is observed by most everyone.

I really enjoyed checking out the map room in one of the top floors. If you go in the evening, you'll have many rooms and aisles to yourself. And many of the reading nooks are quite private, while providing a nice view of the surrounding architecture.

This is a great stop if you're touring around downtown on foot. I was here in February, and it was a lovely place to warm up and read a little. A lot of people seem to avoid the library because of the homeless folks who frequent it, but they're the public too, and I had no negative interactions with anyone. It was a clean, quiet and comfortable environment.
The central library is huge! There are quiet spaces on the top floor. There are so many nooks and crannies in this place that there is always a spot to sit. Check out peak picks for popular titles.

Why a dynamic group of visitors at this library? Half of the attendees are legitimately here to conduct their study and the other half are the homeless of Seattle, charging their phones and enjoying the free newspapers and magazines. Apart from the amazing architecture, a browse around the floors will give you a very good cross section of Washington State.

I absolutely adore this library! The building has a very relaxed, modern style with so many giant open spaces that it never feels crowded, even when there must be at least a thousand people. I come here often to read and work.

reviews.text: Must! It's soo good. Was walking by around lunch and the line was around the corner! I decided to come back after my errands. The line was shorter by 2pm but still outside. Was soo worth the wait. Don't miss out!
Best pastrami sandwich ever. You have to try it! It's called tat'strami sandwich. The only thing I ever get because it has so much flavor and don't forget the Russian sauce!

What kind of sandwich are you feeling like?  Doesn't matter; they've got you covered and every options is a hit.  My standby is still the tatstrami, but the cheesesteak, chicken parm, and others are all good.  Get your fries with the old bay.  There's a web cam to clue you in on how busy it is, but if it's lunch  time, you don't need to check because you know it's busy.
Dear lawd... Tatsrami is for me, others love the Philly cheesesteak. Either way, top it off with a PBR for the ultimate lunch.

Don't get a cheese steak. That would be a big mistake. The Tat'strami is definitely the best sandwich on the menu. The 12" is more than enough to put you to sleep for the afternoon. I like mine with extra Russian. The cheese steak is good, but doesn't come close to the Tat'strami. Split the Crispy Chicken buffalo sandwich with someone last time I went and was also very good. Some of the best sandwiches in Seattle are served here. Salumi, Un Bien, Tat's, and George's Sausage and Deli are my favorites in Seattle.

Our guide was AMAZING! It poured in us halfway through but it was still a blast :)
Some of the greatest info I've heard on a tour! Cody was a fantastic guide! The route was fun and beautiful! Would strongly suggest for both visitors and locals!

We had an awesome tour guide. We were only in Seattle for one day and I felt like because of this tour we got to really get a feel for Seattle. The Segway are super easy to get comfortable on. We had a blast.
I enjoyed this Segway experience and recommend it. I was hesitant at first but I am glad I gave it a try.

reviews.text: Very cool piece of architecture to visit. Be prepared- it is a very humid environment. Super cool way to showcase a lot of cool plants and create a nature filled experience even though you are downtown Seattle.

Beautiful architecture! The Spheres are an amazon workplace. You cannot go in if you are not an employee. You can see through the glass indoors the trees and workstations. Outdoor area very green and well preserved. Nice to walk
Beautiful place

One of the unique touristy places to visit downtown Seattle. This site has some 800 plant species and over 40k plants. Amazon employees can work out of here with access to wifi. Coffee and snacks on sale as well. It gets a bit humid, so might be uncomfortable for some folks with higher than normal sensitivity. Check out the nest or take a pic by the â€œSpheresâ€ sign on one of the floors.
Couldn't go inside, too bad they have entrance available for public 1st and 3rd Saturday of the month. So if anyone plans to go inside the spheres plan wisely.

I'm generally not a doughnut fan, but wow, these were great!  Had six (small) plain doughnuts bagged straight out of the fryolator.  The espresso was also very very good.  Cash only.  Very friendly service.  Nice seating by the window between them & the bagel shop.

I do like this place.  It's a pike place market tradition.  
Simple fast and clever flavor combos.  When you order a cinnamon sugar they just put c & s in the bag and shack the plain donuts all up in it!

When I asked the clerk how he was he responded with a smile "I'm dying inside"  that'll throw ya for a loop ;) Loved him that much more.  Nice folks really.  Don't be afraid to engage and make their day awesome as much as they do for us.

The general line up you can always expect is maple, bacon maple, sugar & cinnamon, plain and powdered sugar.  There is usually a special as well.

OH MY DELICIOUS HEAVEN BISCUITS! Never before have I actually had emotions for a food, but that all changed this weekend. These little dudes descend from the pearly gates right down to your mouth in multiples of 6 and are, simply put, the best donuts we've ever had! Each one was a yummy hug of love!

You watch the donuts go from dough to golden goodness right before your eyes as they go from the pan into the fryer and then, via conveyor belt, into the bowl where they wait for you to take one plus five of his friends home! 

Flavors of plain, cinnamon and sugar, powdered and chocolate w/ sprinkles are your everyday donuts de jour and are amazing. The PLAIN AND CINNAMON SUGAR COME OUT HOT - the way a true donut should. Outsides were crispy and golden brown with a fluffy inside. These dudes and dudettes are mini donuts and thus it's pretty easy for two people to house a dozen. For 6 assorted, we paid less than 3 bucks! 

The peeps manning the station were definitely Seattle fare and very nice. The coffee was solid - I had a shot in the dark (espresso in coffee) and it was better than I've had most places. They counter is adorned by many an action figure including the teenage mutant ninja turtle Raphael - The one who was rough around the edges, but with a heart of gold - just like this place!

You need to try this place - it's straight up amazing! These donuts are inexpensive, but far and away better than anything we've had. A couple steps up from crispy cream and just plain fun. Try this place and you won't be disappointed!

I haven't had a donut in years. I missed them.  I found these to be .... Okay .... And expensive .... Not worth it. 

It is a tradition .. Not worth it.
Good prices, great donuts. Small sizes, but big quantities. They come in half dozen or whole dozen packs.

Whether you are visiting the Pike Place Market for the first time, or have lived here for years, you will find something new and delightful on an Eat Seattle Tour. There are well-known stories about the Market, but there are dozens of secrets, and stories that only a behind-the-scenes tour of the Market will reveal. Get to know WHO your food comes from, not just WHERE, and sample some of the best treats available from an assortment of Market vendors. You haven't seen the Market until you've seen it with Eat Seattle Tours.

What an incredible experience! The food was delicious, the instruction was fun and informative, and it was a hands on experience! They're truly interested in connecting the community to the farmers around us. We learned about the history of Pike's Place, where and when to get the freshest produce, and how to make some Northwest cuisine. This is a business I can stand behind.

We came for a team outing but I would come back with my family or for a date/night out.
Excellent chef guided walking tour of Pikes Market. Liz guided us with a nice combination of market history, insider information, and fantastic tastings.

Great experience, tons of interesting information from Chef Alex and delicious food from both Eat Seattle and the market. I've been to Pike Place Market probably a hundred times and hadn't visited several of the stops on the tour. So glad I went and wish I'd had sooner!

I took one of the Winter in The Market classes, which was great. Liz and her team led a great class and market tour in the beginning while we picked up ingredients for the class. This isn't your typical cooking class. They are very engaging and obviously care a lot about the market and where they get their food.

reviews.text: Loved this trip to the Aquarium. We saw all the otters and boy were they showing off! The seals were putting on a show of their own. So many beautiful fish and so many people enjoying themselves.  It was a great day.
Very cute aquarium. The best part is that there are not too many people here. It was not crowded when we came to visit. They has a beautiful selection of fish. The sea lions were also very cute.

A little pricey but everything was totally worth it. There was all sorts of species of fish to see, and the habitats they made were very cool. There's a downstairs room which lets you completely be "underwater" in a cool dome thing. Cool place to check out and a great place to take the kids. There is a gift shop at the end that had some pretty cool stuff as well.

My son loves walking around this place and splashing in the water. I don't think he can reach the sea anemone in the tide pools yet, but he skims the top of the water and loves that part the most. He is 19 months old and not really interested in the aquarium type exhibits, but the hands on tide pools and aviary and fish dome was his fave. Mine too actually. I'm excited to come try toddler Time at some point.

Had a great visit to the aquarium over Labor Day Weekend. We expected some pretty large crowds, the middle of the afternoon was fairly easy to manage. The exhibits include a touch tank, large displays, and some educator lead talks about the ocean habitat and its creatures.

reviews.text: We were with another couple in Seattle and were looking for a great steakhouse. The Capital Grille was located within walking distance of our hotel. We arrived a bit ahead of our reservation time but we were seated promptly. Servers were informative and helpful and friendly. Plan to make an evening out of dining as there were long breaks between bread, cocktails and main course. Not inattentive but just slower than I expect or enjoy. We split a salad and main course as we had snacked earlier and were not super hungry. Items were brought to the table split which was great! Steak was ordered medium and it came to the table with very little pink. Overall, good meal with great atmosphere and good service.

The service was exceptional. Our waiter, Matthew Camozzi was amazing. He was attentive, but not overbearing. His suggestions were spot on. The evening was pleasant and relaxed. The food was exquisite and exceeded our expectations. I highly recommend NOT missing out on an opportunity to eat here.  Well worth the money!

Great food, atmosphere, prices are good for the type of restaurant it is. Waiters know they're stuff. Deserts are delicious.. crab cakes and lobster bisque are some of the best I've ever had.. great place for an anniversary dinner

First time going there but definitely not the last. Everything from the first bite to last was perfect... Salad, lobster & crab cakes had a ton of meat, steaks were perfect. Would give 10 stars if possible. Service was amazing.  Give that waiter Aram Carter a raise cause he was great. Definitely telling everyone I know to give it a try.
Great service as in all the Capital restaurants.  Salmon salad was really good. Loved the mango pieces, salmon was seared outside, rare inside, and tasted like it just came off the boat
